    <h1>Topoi</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Bartosz Milewski · 2017 · <a href="https://bartoszmilewski.com/2017/07/22/topoi/">Category Theory for Programmers, Ch. 23</a></p>

    <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mb-6">Prereqs: <a href="/reading/category-theory/milewski-11/">🍞 Ch11 (Limits and Colimits)</a>, <a href="/reading/category-theory/milewski-09/">🍞 Ch9 (Function Types)</a>. 10 min.</p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">A <strong>topos</strong> is a category that behaves like a universe of sets. It has all finite limits, exponentials (function objects), and a <strong>subobject classifier</strong> &Omega; that generalizes true/false. In <strong>Set</strong>, &Omega; = &lbrace;true, false&rbrace; and subsets correspond to characteristic functions. In a presheaf topos, &Omega; can have more truth values: the internal logic is intuitionistic, not classical.</p>
    </div>

