    <!-- Translation notes -->
    <h3>Translation notes</h3>
    <p>The blog post is conceptual rather than code-heavy: no Haskell implementations appear. This page translates the definitions into executable Scheme and Python. The subobject classifier in Set is straightforward (characteristic functions are just indicator functions). The presheaf example uses the simplest non-trivial category (two objects, one non-identity arrow) to show that &Omega; can have three truth values. In general, &Omega;(c) is the set of all sieves on c, which can be large. The Heyting algebra section demonstrates the linear order (false &lt; partial &lt; true); in richer presheaf categories, the truth values form a more complex partial order. The blog post also discusses the connection between topoi and alternative foundations of mathematics: topos theory provides a framework where "true" means "provable," aligning with constructive mathematics and type theory.</p>

